In [14]:
categorical = termdep_df.select_dtypes(['object']).columns
for i, cat in enumerate(categorical):
    plt.figure(i)
    ax = sns.countplot(data=termdep_df,x=cat,hue='Target')
    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=40, ha="right")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Analyzing the categorical columns aginst the differen type of target variable.
Job: Since overall count itself has majority no, we cant comment much on the ratio of spread. As we have seen already on value_counts the blue-collar job holders are more in the given population. Also there are less students since th given age group starts at 18. In the age group >60 records are less (753) hence retried count also less over here.
Marital: Majority of the count in the given population is married again it could be due to the age group given. Education: In the given popluation secondary category is having high count
Default: It is credit default, if they are defaulter then they are not opting for term deposit. Out of 815 total defaulters only 50+ people have opted for term deposit.
Housing: Majority of the people in the population has housing loan. If they have housing loan and ratio is less in opting for term deposit. The other way, if they dont have housing loan and the ratio is more in opting for Term deposit.
Loan: Personal loan, the majority of the population did not take the personal loan.
Contact: Majority of the crowd looking for contact through cellphone.
Month: last contacted month of the year, There are quite a lot of people contacted during May month and rest of the year it is less. Irrespective of number of people contacted, the people subscribed is similar through the year, except the year end(dec) due to the fact that people will be on vacation and does not bother about investments.
poutcome: Previous Campaign outcome. Here majority of the cases are failure.

In [18]:
#reusable methods for trying out multiple models 
def getXy(df,exlfeatures=[]):
    target_column = 'Target'
    X = df.drop(target_column, axis= 1)
    X = X.drop(exlfeatures, axis = 1)
    y = df[target_column]
    return X,y
In [19]:
#reusable methods for trying out multiple models 
def addRow(df,ls):
    numEl = len(ls)
    newRow = pd.DataFrame(np.array(ls).reshape(1,numEl), columns = list(df.columns))
    df = df.append(newRow, ignore_index=True)
    return df
In [20]:
#reusable methods for trying out multiple models 
def classificationModel(model, X,y,df):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=.30, random_state=1)   
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_predict = model.predict(X_test)
    score = model.score(X_test, y_test)
    precision, recall,fscore,support = metrics.precision_recall_fscore_support(y_test, y_predict, average='weighted')
    df = addRow(df,[model.__class__.__name__, score, precision, recall])
    return df
In [21]:
op_columns = ['model_name','accuracy','recall','precision']
In [22]:
def doModelling(X,y):
    output_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = op_columns)
    model = LogisticRegression(solver='lbfgs',max_iter = 4000)
    output_df = classificationModel(model,X,y,output_df)
    model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors= 3 , weights = 'distance' )
    X_z = X.apply(zscore)
    output_df = classificationModel(model,X_z,y,output_df)
    model = svm.SVC(gamma=0.025, C=3)
    output_df = classificationModel(model,X,y,output_df)
    return output_df
In [23]:
def doEnsembleModelling(X,y,output_df):
    rmodel = RandomForestClassifier()
    output_df = classificationModel(rmodel,X,y,output_df)
    model = AdaBoostClassifier(base_estimator=rmodel, n_estimators=50,learning_rate=1)
    output_df = classificationModel(model,X,y,output_df)
    model = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state = 100,max_depth=3, min_samples_leaf=5)
    output_df = classificationModel(model,X,y,output_df)
    model = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=20, learning_rate=1, max_features=2, max_depth=2, random_state=1)
    output_df = classificationModel(model,X,y,output_df)
    model = XGBClassifier(objective="binary:logistic", random_state=42)
    output_df = classificationModel(model,X,y,output_df)
    return output_df
